# My understanding experience here was mainly the behaviour of the def functions and how to use the return function to be able to re-use variables stored inside a function block, also that must always use a placeholder if the 
# argument has a function between the patenthesis ( ) or else the function will be waiting for an argument in order to execute the code block
# python always reads code from top to bottom in order no matter what or how you type code
# when trying to re use the variables from the previous def code block the return will allow you to do so or else you will get an error
# input only interacts with strings, if you need a different data type for an iperation while using input you must convert it before: ex num = (int(input('> write any number)), make sure the data type goes accordingly or it could throw an error  
# if you print a variable with many decimals use this format : .1f or : .2f, etc inside the {} where the variable would be placed
# use the start symbol * to unpack a variable, etc and fill it up in more than one argument, its used when you need to unpack a variable that contains more than one data inside it and unpack it in two or more variables of text

def hotel (user):
    print (f'welcome to the hotel Transilvania user {user} ')
    input('> Press ENTER to continue')

    budget = (int(input("> Enter your budget")))
    room = budget / 2.8
    services = room * 1.2
    print (f'With a budget of ${budget: .1f},there is a room available of ${room: .1f} a night and services will cost ${services: .1f}')
    input (f'> {user} the process has been completed press ENTER to exit')
    return budget, room, services


